title: The i5 is perfect for my needs
content: The i5 has always been my processor of choice. I don't need the i7, and I'd rather have the reliability of Intel over AMD. The i5 is perfect for my needs. Heavy gaming, Adobe Photoshop, Premiere, Flash, Illustrator, InDesign all run flawless. No issues with heat on a ThermalTake NiC F4 cooler, even when utilizing my SLI setup. Never goes over 65C. I highly recommend for gaming, as the i7 is simply not needed. It's been proven that the i7 only gives a 5-10% increase in performance over the i5 because games are not utilizing more than 4 cores at this time. That small performance increase is just not worth the extra $110+ for me.
date: Reviewed in the United States on May 2, 2016

title: Won't be buying from BeachAudio again
content: Ordered from BeachAudio:  I won't be buying from BeachAudio again.  What I received was a tray chip, not a boxed chip.  Tray chips are sold in bulk to system builders like Dell or HP and don't have any warranty to speak of.  Tray processors are cheaper, this item is full price.  All my tests have worked so far, but based on the items photo and part number, I was expecting a boxed processor not a tray processor.  I can't speak to other sellers, YMMV.
date: Reviewed in the United States on October 11, 2019

title: Intel Core i5-4690 Processor.

It runs cool and runs hard. Temps are in the middle 20c. Put it on a Asus Z97 board which has expired already.This CPU supports 1333 and 1600MHz memory natively. The taller speeds you have to monkey with the BIOS.Also supports many office type applications.  Contains Intel 4600 graphics which are fine for every day use. The price tag was very good.Fast and a lot of fun while it lasted. Ordered another board, I be up again shortly.Delivered on time, packed well.

title: Its just what I needed

I was using an AMD FX Vuschera 4.0ghz before with quad core, and had the gigabyte 970 8GB of ram, on arma 3 I would normally get 20-45 FPS at 1920x1080p. After I put together my new pc which uses the i5 instead of the FX, all other hardware, minus motherboard, stay the same, I was getting between 45-70 FPS at 1920x1080p. I checked the FPS based on a Breaking Point US Servers and used nvidia shadow play for the FPS Counter. Needless to say, I am very happy that I finally got this processor, and since I don't intend to Overclock, this is perfect for me. If you intend to overclock, and don't need hyperthreading, you may check out the i5-4690k.

title: incredibly Fast!
content: This processor is worth every penny. I do a lot of Video Converting, and it was a pain having to wait 30 mins to convert a 25 minute video. Now with this processor, I can convert a 25 minute video in 3 Minutes! if that gives you any idea as to how fast it is. That turbo boost kicks in and she just starts flying! Every other task has been surprisingly fast as well. This thing just blows right through everything I throw at it. I mainly bought it for gaming but, I do also convert videos A LOT so this processor is good for everything I needed it for. I haven't actually gotten to play any games using it yet, but I can tell just by how much of an improvement it is over my last CPU, that games wont be an issue for this processor.Here's some of what I have on my PC right now.- OS - Windows 8.1- CPU - Intel i5 4690 3.5 Ghz- RAM - 8 GB DDR3 1600 Mhz- Motherboard - MSI Z87-G45 Gaming- PSU - 620 Watt- GPU - Integrated Graphics Motherboard/CPU (No Graphics Card yet) Picture looks GREAT!---------PROS---------Incredibly FastRuns through everything I throw at it with easeSuper quietVery solid 3.5 Ghz with 3.9 Ghz Turbo that automatically kicks in when needed.If you're not looking to overclock, this is the one you want.--------CONS---------None.

title: This processor is amazing!
content: I'm using it in a PC running Windows 2012 Server R2 with 16GB (soon to add 16GB more) RAM and 4 HDs.  I'm hosting 4 Win 8.1 Hyper-V VMs on it while using it also as a front end of a HTPC and notice no performance issues whatsoever related to the processor.VM1 is a PLEX video server (for Rokus and Chromecasts) and "NAS" (just a Windows 8.1 share) to deliver videos to XBMC front end running on the server host OS itself.VM2 is my son's PC, accessed at his desk via a Wyse thin client.VM3 is my PC that I use for all my personal stuff, accessed via anything I have my hands on at the moment (Chromebook/Windows laptops, android tablets/phones, etc.).VM4 is used as a downloader and hosts any other types of server software I need to run.I also installed another NIC for better network performance.  The only performance hit I noticed was because the VMs were all hosted on one HD and my HDs are normal speed.  I moved 2 of the VMs' VHDX files to a different HD and BAM!  All VMs are now super fast.  I'm barely teasing the power of this processor and probably could have got away with an i3.  But I always like to leave some elbow-room so I'm very happy.
date: Reviewed in the United States on March 11, 2015

title: The 4690 and 4690k are the go to processors for gaming with some multimedia
content: Fantastic processor all around that runs very cool for the performance it puts out. It can do everything I throw at it and if all you are doing is gaming do yourself a favor and DO NOT get the i7 or Xeon. Many games only utilize at max 4 cores, but usually just 2 if that. Games benefit from higher clock speeds and not more cores. If you want a processor for only multimedia/production/video editing this processor will work, but you will see much bigger performance gains with a quad core Xeon or i7 with hyper threading and at least 8 or more virtual cores. AMD is a decent choice at the sub $100 level or so, but after that, even if you have to pay a little more upfront you will earn it back on your energy bill. Especially with haswell your computer will run so quickly reliably was well. All around you can't go wrong with this processor for gaming.

title: Perfect for HTPC and most uses
content: This Haswell processor shines! It is low energy consumption, yet one of the quickest on the market. Because it's Haswell, it handles video better than previous generations of Intel. I put this on an ASUS H97 and I have the perfect, yet relatively inexpensive and energy efficient, home theater PC. Anime fans: this processor handles 10-bit AKA Hi10P with no problems. Also should work fine for 3D. It should also be fine for media editing and even gaming, though the most hardcore gamers may be looking for something that overlocks.ONE NOTE: I have a small room and found the included fan made a sort of wailing sound that was annoying. I replaced with a Noctua Silent Cooler.

title: Long time system builder's point of view.
content: I will say after using both AMD and Intel computer builds off and on for years. The power efficiency of Intel cpus rock. As for mind blowing performance over a top Amd cpu it's only a few seconds here and a few seconds there faster. It's a solid cpu for sure. but, I don't feel it's worth what they are charging vs amd pricing. Most people would be hard pressed to tell the difference in real world usage. With the exception of video coding and or graphics rendering. Where intel has a ok advantage in speed not mind blowing,  but a advantage none the less.

title: Awesome Performer
content: This will be used for a long time. People still game on i7 920's and with Vulkan and DX12 benchmarking well, these CPU's are going to last a long time now. It's in my friends computer but compared to my 4770k the general experience is no different. Checking benchmarks, the difference in performance in games is limited to only a few games that truly scale well with more threads. So far I've heard no complaints from him as he plays games or works on improving his ability with the Adobe Creative Cloud, Blender, or Unity game engine. The thing is a beast and will most likely last a long time. If anything, the thing will last forever if used as a general usage PC like how my parents use my old Phenom II 925 PC.
